  "top_findings": [
    "83.0% of trajectories end SETTLED — the corpus is overwhelmingly success-biased (survivorship), endpoint entropy only 0.938 bits.",
    "Median settlement velocity (RECORDED→SETTLED): 6.60 years across 4064 measurable trajectories.",
    "Reversal rate among ever-SETTLED trajectories: 3.72% (186/5005).",
    "The trajectory corpus is genuinely multi-community: only 47.74% of ratification events are EXPERT_LITERATURE (INSTITUTIONAL 3792, PUBLIC 1441, JUDICIAL 729, MARKET 90) — unlike the ~94% expert-dominated ER corpus at large.",
    "Average trajectory depth 2.08 transitions; 13.73% of trajectories took a \"detour\" (depth>2, i.e. a contestation/reversal/re-recording before settling), and 14.09% touched CONTESTED at some point.",
    "Once SETTLED, knowledge is sticky-but-not-permanent: P(stay settled)=0.3474, P(reverse)=0.2797, P(re-contest)=0.2902. CONTESTED claims resolve to SETTLED 62% of the time."
  ],
  "anomalies": [
    "RECORDED→REVERSED in trajectory subset: 180 (vs 5,728 across ALL ClaimStatusHistory — confirms that figure is noise from non-trajectory claims).",
    "Settlement velocity is extremely right-skewed: median 6.60y but mean 222.9y and max 2014.93y — ancient claims (emergedAt centuries before the SETTLED marker) inflate the mean. Use the median.",
    "Within the trajectory subset EXPERT_LITERATURE is only 47.74% of events — NOT the ~94% seen across all ER claims. The trajectory corpus is deliberately multi-community; the global expert-dominance is an artifact of other (non-trajectory) ingestion pipelines."
  ]
